      <p>The <strong>Satechi Thunderbolt 4</strong> dock is our runner-up. It uses the same Thunderbolt 4 controller as the TS4 and supports dual 4K@60Hz with 96W charging. The trade-off is port count — Satechi ships 9 ports versus CalDigit's 18. If you only need a few downstream Thunderbolt ports and want a slimmer design, the Satechi is $100 less and almost as good.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Anker 555</strong> is the budget champion. At $150 it has 8 ports, 85W charging, and supports a single 4K display at 60Hz over HDMI. It will not drive dual 4K monitors, but for a one-monitor MacBook setup it is the best value we tested. If you have a 14-inch MacBook and one external display, this is the dock to buy.</p>

      <p>The <strong>OWC Thunderbolt Dock</strong> is solid but has a small fan that becomes audible under load, and the firmware update process is fiddly. It is a good dock, but the TS4 is better for the same kind of money.</p>

      <p>For travelers who want a smaller option, see our <a href="/reviews/best-usb-c-hub-macbook/">USB-C hub guide</a>. Hubs cannot match a dock on ports or charging, but they fit in a laptop bag. Pair your dock with a <a href="/reviews/best-portable-monitor-work/">portable monitor</a> for a complete desktop-on-the-road setup, and a <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> to raise your MacBook to eye level.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the CalDigit TS4 if you have a dual 4K monitor setup and a MacBook Pro, or if you want the most future-proof dock available. At $399 it is not cheap, but it is the only dock we tested that handled everything we threw at it without a single reconnect or signal drop in 60 days. It will likely outlast several MacBook upgrades.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. CalDigit runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the TS4 drops to $329 to $349. We have seen it as low as $299 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Choose the Anker 555 if you have a single external monitor and a 14-inch MacBook. You save $250 and get the same daily experience for one-monitor users. The TS4's value comes from dual 4K support and 18 ports — if you do not need either, do not pay for them.</p>

      <p>Check your MacBook's chip before buying. Base M1 MacBooks support only one external display regardless of dock. M1 Pro, M1 Max, M2 Pro, M3, and M3 Pro chips support dual displays. If you have a base M1 MacBook and want dual monitors, you need a dock with DisplayLink technology (not Thunderbolt) — and those have their own trade-offs.</p>

      <p>Skip no-name docks on Amazon. Many claim "dual 4K" but cap the second display at 30Hz, throttle charging under load, and overheat during sustained transfers. Stick with CalDigit, Satechi, Anker, OWC, or Belkin. Plan to keep the dock for several MacBook cycles — the TS4's Thunderbolt 4 standard will outlast several laptops.</p>

      <p>Complete your desk setup with proper cable management. A dock solves port anxiety but creates cable clutter — see our <a href="/reviews/best-cable-management-desk/">cable management guide</a> to hide the dock's cables for good. A <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> raises your MacBook to monitor height, which completes the ergonomic picture.</p>

